[1] American Samoa
Date: Thu 23 Aug 2007
Source: Radio New Zeland International [edited]
<http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=34624>

The Health Department in American Samoa is awaiting test results for
a 10-year old boy who died recently at the LBJ hospital with symptoms
of dengue fever. There have been 78 confirmed cases of dengue fever
since January [2007].
The Communicable Disease Nurse for Public Health, Charmaine Edwards,
says blood samples have been sent to Honolulu. She says while there's
awareness about the disease, some are not taking the necessary precautions.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Brent Barrett
******
[2] Yap (suspected): RFI
Date: Fri 7 Sep 2007
From: Dr. Martin Bel
<yapepinet@fsmhealth.fm>

Possible dengue fever cases found in Yap State, Federated States of Micronesia
---------------------------------------------------
During the first week of September [2007], 6 cases meeting the
Pacific Public Health Surveillance Network's dengue fever clinical
case definition presented to Yap outpatient clinics .
On 6 Sep [2007], 4 of the 6 tested positive for dengue [virus
antibody] using Pentax rapid IgM tests. Serum is being sent for
confirmation. None of the cases required hospitalization.
An important caveat: during Yap's recent Zika outbreak, it was found
that Zika IgM will elicit a positive result on rapid IgM dengue
tests. This will affect the specificity of the rapid IgM tests for
dengue in Yap because much of our community was exposed to the Zika
virus in April, May and June [2007]. Therefore confirmation will be
especially important.
Yap State's initial response is being coordinated by the Yap Epinet
team. While awaiting confirmation, the Epinet Team has already
started to respond to a likely dengue outbreak with usual
surveillance enhancement, outbreak control measures, and utilization
of clinical guidelines. Support and supplies previously donated by
the WHO and [USA's] CDC for the recent Zika outbreak have already
played in an important role in the initial response to these suspect cases.
--
Dr. Martin Bel
Chairman, Yap Epinet Team
<yapepinet@fsmhealth.fm>
[ProMED again thanks Dr. Bel for providing timely information about
this outbreak and their response to it. Given the cross-reactivity of
flavivirus antibody, the Yap team is justifiably cautious about
definitely identifying dengue virus as the etiological agent. _Aedes_
vector mosquito control would be the same to interrupt transmission
of both dengue & Zika viruses. - Mod.TY]
[It is puzzling as to how these cases differ clinically from the Zika
cases they had recently, as both give fever, joint pains and rash. I
wonder why they don't think they are just a recrudescence of the Zika
virus outbreak? - Mod.JW]
[A map of Micronesia can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/islands_oceans_poles/micronesia_pol99.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]
