[3] Brazil (Sao Paulo, Mato Grosso do Sul)
Date: 27 Aug 2007
Source: Globo.com [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/SaoPaulo/0,,MUL94732-5605,00.html>

Caraguatatuba has the most dengue cases in its history
-------------------------------------------------------
Currently, there are 808 persons infected [with dengue virus] from
_Aedes aegypti_ bite in the municipality. In 2004, 502 cases were
registered. The number of confirmed dengue cases in Caraguatatuba
(173 km [107.5 miles] from Sao Paulo) has never been so high.
Ricardo de Sousa, coordinator of the dengue combat team of
Caraguatatuba, confirmed that during the height of the epidemic,
together with the Superintendancy of Epidemic Control, [they] carried
out chemical house-to-house [vector] control. "The municipality has a
larval density of 1.4 percent. There have been 808 [dengue] cases
registered and 1360 notified, which represents an emergency
situation," he said. [It is not clear what the difference is between
registered & notified. - Mod.JW]
This year [2007] 59 498 dengue cases have been registered in the
state of Sao Paulo. The hot, rainy summer weather, along with the
intense circulation of dengue [virus] 3, and [Sao Paulo's] proximity
to Mato Grosso do Sul [state] (which has experienced the worst
[dengue] epidemic in its history), are the principal factors
[responsible for the current dengue outbreak] scene in Sao Paulo.
--
