[7] Taiwan
Date: 22 Aug 2007
Source:China Post [edited]
<http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/2007/08/22/119338/Dengue-fever.htm>

Another 89 cases of dengue fever were reported around Taiwan last
week [9-15 Aug 2007], including 44 cases involving residents in a
veterans' home in Tainan City's East District, a Department of Health
(DOH) official said yesterday [21 Aug 2007]. Chou Chih-hau, deputy
director-general of the DOH's Center for Disease Control (CDC), said
the cluster in Tainan was the largest in nearly 10 years.
The 1st case of the cluster was reported 8 Aug [2007] followed by
more cases on 13 and 14 Aug [2007]. Tainan City's Health Bureau and
the [Taiwan] CDC then started examinations of residents and inspected
the environment around the veterans' home, which houses more than 400
veterans in their 70s or 80s. The CDC discovered that 44 residents
were infected with dengue fever and found that drains on the roof and
water reservoirs of the facility's air conditioners were the main
mosquito breeding areas.
Chou said elderly people infected with dengue fever do not show
obvious symptoms of rash and high fever of up to 39 degrees C [102.2
degrees F]. He reminded nursing homes to heed the situation and clean
water storage containers around residences to avoid another cluster
of infection.
Chou said the North District of Tainan City also reported its 2nd
indigenous dengue fever case -- a 2-year-old girl who was diagnosed
with the disease 6 Aug [2007]. She was discharged from the hospital
17 Aug [2007].
Meanwhile, Kaohsiung County officials responsible for health and
environmental protection affairs were mobilized for an urgent
undertaking aimed at preventing an outbreak of dengue fever. County
Magistrate Yang Chiu-hsiung ordered officials to reinforce efforts to
cleanse mosquito-breeding sites after the southern county reported
last week its first indigenous dengue fever case this summer. The
patient, a woman aged over 50, resides in the county's Fengshan City
but works in the neighboring city of Kaohsiung, County Director of
Health Huang Chih-chung said, noting that Kaohsiung City is one of
southern Taiwan's dengue-affected areas, with 52 cases of indigenous
dengue fever reported so far since the beginning of the summer.
[of 2007].
--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Brent Barrett
